inputs.text: WeForest Tree Planting ğŸŒ±  @weforest_org  are an organization that we have worked with for a long time in our tree planting endeavors. Through them, we have planted trees in Madagascar, India, Zambia and Oregon. WeForest are supporting 75 traditionally forest-dependent villages in the east and north of the Khasi Hills in India to restore their forests by establishing natural fire lines to protect the forest and restoring endangered flora. WeForest are also working to reverse deforestation by supporting local farmers in Luanshya to be financially independent in return for protecting the Miombo woodlands, and adopting sustainable farming methods such as bee-keeping, egg-rearing and vegetable-growing.  Farmers are also receiving training and support to establish home-based nurseries to increase forest growth. WeForest also support farmers in gaining ownership of the land in order to secure sustainability and longevity of the conservation and livelihood outcomes.

That's why we've partnered with award winning mixologist Walter PintusÂ @waltz16  to show you how to make the most of your cocktail ingredients (and prep for your next cocktail party in doing soğŸ¸)   *Because a #LifeHack shared is a problem solved, is it not?  You will need: A small Tupperware container - mortar or blender - saucepan - oven   Fruit breakdown / deconstruction  Pulp - juice - skin - stone  Using all of the fruit you can obtain 3-4 different ingredients for different uses.  1. Make a fruit syrup with a technique called Oleo saccharum: - this is a way of producing a very aromatic sugar-oil mixture by coating citrus or other oil-rich fruit rinds in an excess of sugar and letting it macerate for 24 hours. The liquid obtained can be used as a sweet base for cocktails.  2. At this stage you can peel off the skins and dehydrate them to make crunchy apple crisps.   3. The pulp left can be blended to make a fruit purÃ©e for bellinis or even desserts. It can also be dehydrated to make fruit lathers which can be enjoyed as a snack.  4. The core of the apple is very aromatic and has got a distinct flavour once processed. Dry the core over a saucepan or naturally break it down with a mortar and macerate it in sugar and water (1:1) to make an orgeat or almond syrup. â€‹ â€‹For more #LifeHacks, click on through to our websiteÂ ğŸ’»

When Jesse's community was hit hard by the pandemic, he was inspired by his grandfather's memory to help.  "The legacy I want to continue is the values I learned from my dad and grandpa and going out and serving the community. Loving everyone around you," says Jesse.  Part of honoring his grandfather is by staying connected to his heritage, especially as he raises his two children.  "It's important for them to know they are part of this Tribe because it's something they inherited from my grandfather." inputs.text: Photo by @rubensalgadoescudero | Fisherman and builder Lukwago Kaliste, 29, hammers into a rock next to his home in Sango Bay, Uganda. When the evening comesâ€”after a day of fishingâ€”Lukwago breaks large rocks into smaller pieces that he later sells for building the foundations of homes. In three hours, he's able to break enough rocks to fill a small truck, worth about 10 dollars, giving him a much needed extra source of income. Sango Bay is a fishing village with 120 households standing on the shore of Lake Victoria. inputs.text: For store manager Kim, community and sustainability have always been linked. She was able to combine these two passions when she was selected to test a borrow and return cup program in her store.   Kim was involved in teaching her baristas and customers about the new cups and providing feedback to improve the program.  "There was a real sense of community around impacting change,â€ she says. "And our community wanted to be a part of it. It was really exciting."   The program gives customers an easy way to help reduce single-use waste by allowing them to request a reusable cup, take it to-go, then return it later to be professionally cleaned and used again.   For now, the borrow and return cup program only exists in select stores, but Kim says it was met with enthusiasm by partners (employees) and customers alike.   "There's so much willingness to engage with innovation and try new things. I think everyone really does want to contribute to a better world," she says. "And if we can help them do that one cup at a time, that is our mission right there."
